<DESCRIPT>  PALO-ALTO; MAN; PUBLIC; RELATION; MADAGASCAR  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  As you make your way down Garland Drive, a curvy, tree-shaded road in south
Palo Alto, you'll come upon a house that's a little different from the rest.; 
  At the tip of a cul-de-sac sits a simple white home with a bronze plaque at
the entrance, and a grand red, white and green flag flying above the garage.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  P.A. MAN PROMOTES MADAGASCAR
HIS HOME IS HIS CONSULATE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran P. 5B Morning Final Edition  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Welcome to 867 Garland Drive, the Honorary Consulate of the Democratic
Republic of Madagascar, Palo Alto's only consulate, otherwise known as the
home of Jean-Marie "James" de La Beaujardiere and his family.;    With only
eight native Malagasy known to be living in the Bay Area, Palo Alto may seem a
strange site for such a consulate. It's here because de La Beaujardiere, a
native of Madagascar, lives and works in Palo Alto. And when the Madagascar
Embassy wanted help, he volunteered to promote his island homeland, off the
southeast coast of Africa.;    Madagascar, a 24-hour airplane ride from here,
is not well known in America. De La Beaujardiere is used to that.;    "It's
true. Almost everybody has no idea where it is or what it looks like," said de
La Beaujardiere, 54, who coined the nickname "James" after consulate
officials, seeing his first name, thought he was a woman and kept seating him
between two men at official dinners.;    Since de La Beaujardiere turned his
home into a consulate seven years ago, neighbors have gotten used to having a
built-in conversation piece next door.;    "After a while, you don't even
notice it," said Barbara Murray, who lives across the street. "In fact, I
didn't know anything about Madagascar before it opened, and I still don't know
much now.";    De La Beaujardiere opened the consulate when relations between
the United States and Madagascar improved after a tense eight years in the
late 1970s when rumors, later discounted, spread that the CIA was supplying
aid to Madagascar's opposition party.;    De La Beaujardiere works for free as
a consul, when he is not earning a living as a programmer at the Xerox Palo
Alto Research Center. He issues visas, provides information about tourism and
trade, lectures at schools, compiles a computer index of literature on
Madagascar and acts as official host for visiting Malagasy dignitaries.;   
Above all, he said, he wants people in America to learn that "Madagascar is a
beautiful country with extremely unusual plants and animals found nowhere
else," a place where nature lovers would feel right at home.;    The world's
fourth-largest island, 1 1/2 times the size of California, Madagascar boasts
hills, deserts and rain forests, which are being depleted by farmers who burn
down the trees to grow rice, the country's main staple.;    The largely rural
country is known for baobab trees, with their distinct rootlike branches; rich
coffee beans; lemurs, exotic primates with glowing eyes; and for the world's
largest variety of chameleons.;    Madagascar, which gained its independence
from France in 1960, is home to 10 million people, most of whom who are
farmers or herders of either black African or Indonesian descent. It is one of
the world's poorest countries, with an average per capita income of $250 a
year, de La Beaujardiere said.;    De La Beaujardiere grew up in the capital
of Antananarivo. One grandfather was an architect there, and designed many of
the country's elegant churches. Another grandfather started a print shop that
is still operating.;    De La Beaujardiere moved to France because there was
no university in Madagascar at the time, he said. After graduating from
college, he worked as a physicist before moving to Palo Alto 20 years ago with
his wife, Odile, also a physicist, and three sons.;    De La Beaujardiere
maintains that "my flesh is French, my head is American, but my heart is
Malagasy.";    And he hopes that one day, his beloved homeland won't seem
quite so mysterious to those in his new-found land.  </TEXT>
