<LEADPARA>  CONSIDER the life of the top baboon: He appears to call all the shots for his
troop; and he rules a "harem" of females. Young males can stay in the troop,
but they're not permitted to mate.;    Aha! thought the scientists studying
baboon behavior. There must be something biological, something genetic, that
dictates male dominance over females, at least among primates.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Science &amp; Medicine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DOMINANCE ISN'T ALWAYS WHAT IT SEEMS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Biology  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Too bad those scientists didn't study the lemurs of Madagascar instead,
says Sarah Nelson, chairwoman of the Anthropology Department at the University
of Denver.;    Among lemurs, the females wear the pants, as is true in many
societies, says Nelson.;    Nelson currently is leading a series of discussion
groups on the topic of gender differences and how they've been perceived
through history.;    These female lemurs, Nelson said, grab food from the
males, hit them and shove them away. "I'm not putting this forward as ladylike
behavior, but it is an example of a primate where the females are dominant
over the males," she said.;    The males of a different group of lemurs in
Madagascar are the primary child care-givers.;    "As soon as the baby is
born, the mother gives it to a waiting male, who carries it around," Nelson
said. "It hangs onto the male's fur. When the baby gets restless and wants to
nurse, he gives it to the mother. It nurses, then she gives it right back.";  
 And perhaps it's wrong to think of those baboons as the male's harem, Nelson
said. Perhaps it's that the females do the really important work of bearing
young, and they choose to keep just one male around merely to meet their
reproductive needs.;    Nelson cites all these monkey-related anecdotes to
prove her point: Males aren't always the dominant sex.;    Among humans, "The
diminishment of women's role seems to come with warfare," Nelson said. "In
those agricultural societies that are peaceful, women seem to be at least
equal with men."  </TEXT>
