<LEADPARA>  LAST CHANCE TO SEE; By Douglas Adams  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WITH HUMOR AND COMPASSION, AUTHOR TRACKS
VANISHING SPECIES
GETTING A LAST LOOK AT ENDANGERED ANIMALS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Books
Blake Edgar is assistant editor of Pacific Discovery, the natural history
magazine of the California Academy of Science.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  and Mark Carwardine; Harmony Books/Crown, 220 pp., $20; BECAUSE his
grandmother worked for the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals, Douglas Adams' boyhood home sheltered many "badly damaged dogs." But
Adams says he never developed an interest in animals.;    So he was baffled
when a British magazine decided to send him, a best-selling author of comic
science fiction novels, to Madagascar in 1985 to join zoologist Mark
Carwardine on a search for a rare and elusive lemur. This animal, the aye-aye,
made a brief appearance on a tree branch during a downpour, and Adams was
moved to join Carwardine on a second journey to find other endangered
species.;    "Last Chance to See" relates their 1988 trip to a handful of
places where some of the world's rarest animals survive, for the moment.
Alternately uplifting and depressing, the book affirms the need to preserve
other species and their habitats, and reveals what a necessary and difficult
task that is.;    Fans of Adams' "The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy" and
its sequels, or his Dirk Gently detective novels, will recognize the author's
wit and offbeat perspective in his first non-fiction work. There are hilarious
accounts of actually reaching the increasingly unremote spots, as Adams' sense
of intrepid adventure consistently gets dashed.;    Adams brings sensitivity
and curiosity to his encounters with the animals themselves. He also takes the
opportunity to comment and ruminate on the state of his species -- the monkeys
that mastered astounding feats of "twig technology" as they evolved.;    For
instance, while staring into the eyes of a silverback mountain gorilla in a
Zairean cloud forest, Adams ponders the futility of teaching language to apes.
"There are many members of our own species who live in and with the forest and
know it and understand it. We don't listen to them. What is there to suggest
we would listen to anything an ape could tell us?";    Adams' and Carwardine's
quest takes them to New Zealand to search for the kakapo, "the world's
largest, fattest and least-able-to-fly parrot," to Komodo for its legendary
10-foot dragon ("though it doesn't actually breathe fire, it does have the
worst breath of any creature known to man"), to Mauritius where the extinct
dodo lived and where a host of other unique birds barely exist.;    Many of
these locales share a feature that makes them logical settings for a book on
endangered species: They are islands. Evolution assumes amazing forms on
islands, including flightless birds, giant lizards and dwarf mammoths. But
when an island's isolation is broken by exotic predators and colonizing
people, its animals and fragile habitats are quickly overrun.;    Adams and
Carwardine do see all of their selected species in the wild except one, the
baiji, a half-blind dolphin threatened by barbed fishing nets and blaring boat
propellers on China's Yangtze River. But their success is incidental to the
story of how each of these animals became rare and of the sometimes
extraordinary steps being taken to save them.;    Take the kakapo, for
example. Fewer than 50 of these large, khaki parrots exist, confined to three
tiny islands. Saving the kakapo has become the top priority for the New
Zealand Department of Conservation.;    Rats, cats, dogs, ferrets and weasels
arrived with settlers and decimated kakapo eggs and chicks in their
ground-level nests. New Zealand remains unsafe for kakapos, and
conservationists killed feral animals on two smaller islands before turning
them into carefully guarded kakapo refuges.;    Perhaps the bird's biology
presents the biggest obstacle to its future. Female kakapos breed once every
four years and then they lay just one egg.;    Meanwhile, the male kakapo
builds a bowl-shaped stage and emits a deep, booming mating call each night
for months. The only problem is that it's difficult for the prospective mate
to locate the source of the call.;    As Adams writes, "One conservation
worker we met said he sometimes wonders if the mating call of the male didn't
actively repel the female, which is a sort of biological absurdity you
otherwise find only in discotheques.";    Although the animals are the main
characters in "Last Chance to See," Adams does not neglect the dedicated and
hopeful biologists. They include Don Merton, who deposits sweet potatoes at
former courtship sites in New Zealand's Fiordland in case a kakapo or two
persist there; and Professor Zhou, the founder of a "semi-nature reserve" for
the Yangtze river dolphin.;    Adams also peppers the book with curious cameo
characters. There is the Australian venom specialist who's bored with
poisonous animals and whose only advice is "don't get bitten." There is Arab,
the scruffy free-lance kakapo tracker and his kakapo-tracking dog, Boss. Plus
hordes of obnoxious tourists and inept officials.;    One drawback is the
book's focus on conspicuous, flashy species that can easily inspire awe,
admiration and action. Obviously, Adams and Carwardine could choose but a few
species to seek, and in his insightful epilogue, Carwardine points out, "It is
often not the big and beautiful creatures, but the ugly and less dramatic
ones, that we need most.";    "Last Chance to See" offers a poignant portrait
of some scattered patches in our shredded natural tapestry and of the people
rushing to mend what they can. (box)  </TEXT>
