<DESCRIPT>  COMPUTER; SOFTWARE; ENVIRONMENT; GAME; CHILDREN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  FOR PARENTS who want their kids to save the planet instead of shooting up the
place, software publishers have finally begun to offer more environmentally
sensitive products.;    Computer literacy and environmental awareness have
come together in recent years to produce a growing body of "greenware" --
several dozen game-oriented educational titles that embody sound ecological
principles.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Computing  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PLAYING WITH PLANET EARTH
GREENWARE TEACHES CHILDREN ECOLOGY THROUGH GAMES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story;  Additional information attached to the end of this article.; 
(box) FINDING A NICHE: Merchandise at KidTech is strictly child's play. Page 3F  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Even The Nature Company, a trendy retailer of eco- paraphernalia, has begun
to offer a few software titles in its catalog.;    One of the recent arrivals,
Eco-Adventures in the Rain Forest, is typical of this genre. The program
provides a computer simulation of a rain forest. It asks aspiring forest
rangers to complete a series of assignments that require exploration of the
habitat.;    For example, one assignment might be to locate and photograph a
lemur. To complete the task, the adventurer must learn the lemur's habits and
preferences. The search may be complicated by extensive clear-cutting of the
forest, unfavorable weather, the unexpected appearance of other species or
threats from poachers. Indians or anthropologists encountered along the way
might provide more information about the rain forest and its inhabitants.;   
Each assignment ends with a "press conference" back at the ranger station,
where reporters ask questions about the situation.;    Another recent arrival,
Eco-Saurus, is intended to teach conservation to kids in the early elementary
grades. An alien is stranded on a befouled island. The objective is to help
the alien repair his spaceship by finding trash that can be recycled into
essential components and by conserving sufficient water and energy.;   
Although school systems have been using personal computers as instructional
tools for more than a decade, much of the older educational software was
intended to provide drill and practice on academic material. Such programs --
clearly developed for use by captive audiences -- can seem dreadfully dull in
comparison with recent computer games.;    Developers of greenware have relied
heavily upon the game format and the techniques of arcade game developers to
produce products that are less overtly instructional.;    When Bob Stevens and
David Smith designed Earthquest two years ago, they tied together basic
information about the Earth in a format that allowed a user to explore more
detailed material on its land, air, water, animals and people. Individual
frames, for example, showed where volcanoes were found, how they erupted and
when significant eruptions occurred.;    Earthquest seemed to be a
computerized reference book, enlivened at points by small games and quizzes
that provided incentive for exploring more of the program.;    In designing
their second product, Earthquest Explores Ecology, Stevens and Smith made far
greater use of the game format. "Much more effort went into the fun side,"
Stevens said. Their new program functions more like a large game that
frequently requires exploration of a reference work.;    "The game has become
the principal method for stimulating interest in the information," Stevens
said.;    Another recent release, SimAnt from Maxis Software in Orinda,
creates an electronic ant colony. The objective of the game is for the black
ants to defeat the red ants, their competitors for food and territory. After
taking over the entire back yard, the black ants can invade the adjacent home
and drive out human inhabitants. Along the way, the black ants are decimated
by such hazards as insect predators, rainstorms, human feet, lawn mowers and
insecticides.;    To compete successfully in this brutal environment, it is
necessary to learn a good deal about ant castes, breeding and other essentials
of ant citizenship.;    "There's no reason kids can't be learning and having
fun at the same time," said Jeffery Silverman, president of Tanager Software
Productions in San Leandro.;    Silverman's company recently released The
Secret Codes of C.Y.P.H.E.R. -- Operation Wildlife.;    The program puts kids
in the role of an undercover agent responsible for finding and deciphering
secret messages. To find these "cyphergrams," users must learn some basic
information about mammals and locate them in their proper habitat.;   
Developers of greenware must strike a balance between the extraordinary
variation of nature and the limitations of the personal computer. There's a
paradox in trying to represent ecosystems and illustrate environmental
phenomena through a medium that is so far removed from the natural world,
Robinson said.;    Robinson had to combine elements from widely separated
parts of the world into a single generic computerized rain forest. Although
information on any single species is accurate, the result is an improbable
world where an Asian species might coexist with a South American species.;   
"Nature is extremely complex," Silverman said. "We can only go so far in
simulating it."; ECO-SOFTWARE; Here's a sampling of environment-related
programs.; (box)Eco-Adventures in the Rainforest. Published by Chariot
Software. Available in Macintosh and DOS versions. Recommended ages: 9-14.
List Price: DOS or Mac (B&amp;W), $49.95; Mac (color), $59.95.; (box)Eco-Saurus.
Published by First Byte. Available in DOS version only. Recommended ages: 4-9.
List price: $39.95.; (box)Earthquest. Published by Earthquest Inc. Available
in Macintosh and DOS versions. Recommended ages: 10 and up. List price: DOS,
$59.95; Mac, $69.95.; (box)Earthquest Explores Ecology. Published by
Earthquest Inc. Available in Macintosh version only (DOS version to be
released in March). Recommended ages: 10 and up. List price: $59.95.;
(box)SimAnt. Published by Maxis Software. Available in Macintosh version only
(DOS version to be released in January). Recommended ages: 7 and up. List
price: $59.95.; (box)The Secret Codes of C.Y.P.H.E.R. -- Operation Wildlife.
Published by Tanager Software. Available in DOS version only (Macintosh
version to be released in March). Recommended ages: 8 and up. List price:
$49.95.; (box)Eco-Adventures in the Ocean. Published by Chariot Software. This
is the second in a series that began with Eco- Adventures in the Rain Forest.
The objective is to complete a series of oceanographic research assignments.
Available in Macintosh version only. (DOS version to be released in January.)
Recommended ages: 9-14. List Price: Mac (B&amp;W), $49.95; Mac (color), $59.95.;
(box)Balance of the Planet. Published by Chris Crawford Games. This simulation
offers an opportunity to run the world as "Commissioner of the Environment,"
juggling the need for industrial and food production against problems such as
global warming, acid rain and other pollution. Recommended ages: 15 and up.
Available in DOS and Mac versions. List price: $59.95.; (box)SimEarth.
Published by Maxis Software. Another opportunity to rule the world. For those
tired of fine-tuning ocean temperatures and insect populations, SimEarth
offers options such as catastrophic meteors, nuclear accidents and ice ages to
upset the balance. Recommended ages: 12 and up. Available in Macintosh and DOS
versions. List price: $69.95.; (box)Audubon Wildlife: Whales. Published by
National Audubon Society. This is an older and slower-moving, but highly
regarded program. It offers a chance to research migration of whales in the
Pacific or extinction of manatees in Florida, rescue stranded whales or
explore a 19th century whaling village. Available in DOS and Apple II
versions. Recommended ages: 8-17. List price: $49.95 (includes trial
membership in Audubon Society).; (box)Audubon Wildlife: Grizzly Bears.
Published by National Audubon Society. Become a biologist trying to locate
grizzlies and investigate the mysterious death of a bear, or become a park
ranger trying to prevent conflicts between bears and people. Available in DOS
and Apple II versions. Recommended ages: 8-17. List price: $49.95 (includes
trial membership in Audubon Society).; -- Ron Wolf  </TEXT>
