<DESCRIPT>  CONSERVATION; AWARD; US  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ENVIRONMENTAL HEROISM on six continents was celebrated Monday with the
presentation of the second annual Goldman Environmental Prizes, which seem
destined to become the Nobels of save-the-planet activism.;    Founded by San
Francisco philanthropists Richard and Rhoda Goldman and endorsed by the
leaders of 57 nations, including President Bush, the prize honors those who
fight enormous odds -- and sometimes the very heads of state who have endorsed
the prize -- to protect the environment.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOLDMAN PRIZES HONOR EARTH'S BEST FRIENDS
7 ENVIRONMENTALISTS RECOGNIZED FOR EFFORTS
TO PROTECT PLANET  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Richard Goldman, chairman and chief executive officer of Richard N. Goldman
&amp; Co., a major independent insurance brokerage firm, said the prize was
designed to acknowledge "ordinary people doing extraordinary things." He said
it is "based on the premise that individuals can make a difference.";    This
year's winners, who were introduced at a morning news conference at the Clift
Hotel, range from a Swedish schoolboy to a Peruvian jungle tribesman to a San
Francisco biologist with a passion for dolphins.;    Each winner, except the
schoolboy, who shares his prize with a former teacher, will receive $60,000.;
AFRICA: GREEN BELT; 10 million trees; planted in Kenya;  Wangari Maathai was
the first woman from Kenya to earn a doctorate, but the work for which she was
honored Monday was not academic. It began with the simple planting of a tree.;
   Maathai, 51, is founder of Kenya's Green Belt Movement, a tree-planting
project aimed at curtailing the effects of logging practices that cleared all
but 3 percent of her nation's timberlands.;    Employing 50,000 people, mostly
women, the program is credited with planting 10 million trees across the
Kenyan countryside. The movement is so successful that it is being copied in
more than a dozen African nations.;    In 1989, Maathai's commitment to the
environment put her in opposition to plans for a 60-story skyscraper -- billed
as the tallest on the African continent -- in the middle of a park that is
downtown Nairobi's most important public open space. So incensed was the
government that officials labeled her and her movement "subversive" and
threatened her with deportation.;    Maathai persisted, and international
publicity caused foreign investors to withdraw support for the skyscraper,
which has been drastically scaled down and still has not been built.;    On
Monday, Maathai seemed amazed at being labeled a subversive. "As if planting a
tree is an activity that can overthrow any government," she said.; ASIA: RAIN
FORESTS;  Warning: Logging; is bad for Earth;  Yoichi Kuroda of Japan was
rewarded, in effect, for warning his compatriots of the consequences of their
rapacious appetite for tropical hardwood.;    During the past 20 years,
logging by Japanese interests has destroyed most of the forests of Thailand
and the Philippines, and now threatens Malaysia's.;    The international
environmental community long has linked tropical deforestation to such
calamities as drought, floods and economic upheavals, but it is a book that
Kuroda co-authored that is credited with presenting those connections to the
Japanese public.;    In addition to writing "Timber From the South Seas: An
Analysis of Japan's Tropical Timber Trade and its Environmental Impact,"
37-year-old Kuroda led demonstrations to pressure Japanese government and
corporate leaders to change their policies.;    Kuroda said Monday that it is
too early to estimate how much his efforts will reduce timber imports. But he
indicated that he will not be satisfied until rain forest logging ends.;
ANTARCTICA: MINING; Author urges U.S. to stop digging;  Catherine Ceinwen
Wallace of New Zealand used her trip to the United States to pick up her prize
as an opportunity to criticize one of her major foes -- the U.S. government.; 
  Wallace, 39, an author and university lecturer in economics, is pushing for
a ban on mining in the Antarctic, despite opposition primarily from the Bush
administration.;    Wallace, a leader in a movement that includes 200
organizations in 40 countries, cites the Exxon Valdez disaster as an example
of what can happen when oil and other riches are extracted from pristine
environments.;    "Anything you could dig out of the ground has far less value
than other treasures of the Antarctic," she said.; EUROPE: KIDS' FUND; How a
schoolboy; saved a rain forest;  "It's not easy to be a teacher sometimes,"
said Eha Kern of Sweden. "Children ask so many questions.";    One student who
asked a lot of questions was Roland Tiensuu, now 12, who in 1987 was so moved
by Kern's descriptions of tropical rain forests that he organized his
classmates to raise money to save some of the trees and animals.;    A bake
sale raised enough money for Costa Rica's Monteverde Conservation League to
buy a few acres of rain forest in the spectacular Monteverde Reserve.
Heartened by success and guided by Kerns, the students expanded their efforts.
Now, more than 4,000 Swedish schools have joined to raise $1.5 million, enough
to buy more than 17,000 acres.;    In appreciation, the conservation league
has named that section of the reserve "Bosque Eterno d los Ninos" -- The
Children's Eternal Forest.; S. AMERICA: INDIAN LAND; Native tribes; get a
champion;  With his brightly colored hat and feathered earring, Evaristo
Nugkuag looks like what he is -- a member of the Aguaruna tribe of Peru's
Amazon basin.;    But while very much part of his tribe, Nugkuag is educated
in the ways of the larger world and has used that knowledge to help protect
his people. He has persuaded Indians throughout the Amazon regions of Peru,
Bolivia, Ecuador, Brazil and Colombia to join in a coalition that now lobbies
on behalf of 1.2 million indigenous people.;    The Indians have reached out
for international support in the battle against encroachment by ranchers,
miners and developers, arguing that indigenous people are part of the natural
environment of the Amazon and should be allowed to remain there as stewards of
the land.;    "The forest is not a resource for us -- it is life itself,"
Nugkuag said through an interpreter. "It is the only place for us to live.";
N. AMERICA: DOLPHINS; A video changes the tuna industry; Sam LaBudde of San
Francisco was the only prize winner honored for undercover work.;    From
October 1987 to January 1988, LaBudde hired out as a deck hand and cook on a
Mexican fishing boat so he could surreptitiously videotape the slaughter of
hundreds of dolphins trapped in tuna nets.;    His tape, the first filmed
evidence that fishing crews were killing large numbers of dolphins in the
pursuit of tuna, was broadcast widely throughout the world and led to a
boycott that forced major canneries to stop buying tuna caught in ways that
kill dolphins.;    LaBudde, 34, said he would donate the $60,000 to the Earth
Island Institute to save endangered species.;    But LaBudde is not
optimistic. Citing estimates that 10,000 species will become extinct in the
next 10 years, he said that despite such efforts as his own, "the likelihood
is there's not a damn thing we can do about it."  </TEXT>
